<biogHist>
<abstract>The Mental Treatment Act 1927 (18 Geo. V No. 13) allowed people in the general population with 'mental disorders' to be admitted to mental health institutions without the stigma of being certified as insane, but to be subsequently sent to a hospital for the insane involuntarily if they had not 'recovered' within six months.</abstract>
<p>The <span style="font-style:italic"> Mental Treatment Act 1927</span> extended the provisions of the <span style="font-style:italic">Mental Treatment Act 1917</span>, to the general population, including people under the age of 21 years.</p>

</biogHist>
</description>
